'''Yagokorōoichihiko Shrine''' (やごころおおいちひこじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kurobe|Q753864|WD=Q753864|1=Kurobe, Toyama}}, {{ill|lt=Toyama Prefecture|Q132929|WD=Q132929|1=Toyama Prefecture}}. Until the Meiji period it was called “Mishima Daimyōjin”; it was given its current name in Meiji, but is still called '''Mishima Shrine''' today.

It enshrines {{ill|WD=Q386563|lt=Ōyamatsumi|Q386563|WD=Q386563|lt=Ōyamazumi-no-Kami|1=Ōyamatsumi}}, {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|WD=Q3275687|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Kami|1=Sukunabikona}}, and {{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|WD=Q1640658|lt=Kagutsuchi-no-Kami|1=Kagu-tsuchi}} as principal deities, and {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|WD=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu-Ōmikami|1=Amaterasu}} as a merged deity<ref name="p330">''Toyama Prefecture Shrine Gazette'' (published November 10, 1983 by Toyama Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines), p.330.</ref>.

Spring festival is May 5, annual-year festival is February 20, autumn festival is October 4, and Niiname-sai is November 26. Special rites include the Chinowa rite (June 30)<ref name="tt" /> and Jijin Festival (June 25; sacred bamboo is set around the shrine and the event is celebrated with songs and dance)<ref name="tt" /><ref name="p330" />.

The precinct area is 4,000 tsubo, with 13 million ujiko<ref name="p330" />.

=== History ===
There are various theories on foundation: one says it was invited to Sakurai-shō Mikkaichi during the reign of {{ill|lt=Empress Kōken|Q232955|WD=Q232955|1=Empress Kōken}}<ref name="p330" />; another says a {{ill|lt=gohei|Q1011372|WD=Q1011372|1=Gohei}} flew from a mountaintop in Karezawa Village to the east (present Karezawa, Kurobe), stayed in Mikkaichi, and when locals enshrined it, three {{ill|lt=shintai statues|Q11588751|WD=Q11588751|1=Idols in Shinto}} appeared, and so it was revered as “Mishima Daimyōjin”<ref name="rs">''A Historical Walk of Toyama Prefecture'' (Yamakawa Publishing, issued March 31, 2013, 1st ed., 3rd printing), pp.26-27.</ref>. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} it is ranked as a small shrine<ref name="p330" />.

From old times it has been deeply revered from nearby and surrounding areas as a deity of abundant harvests, medicine and brewing, fire protection, and foremost divine protection<ref name="rs" /><ref name="p330" />. It is said that in earlier times imperial messengers were sent, offerings and sacred mirrors were dedicated, and rites were carried out with great solemnity<ref name="p330" />.

One tradition says the name “Mishima Daimyōjin” comes from {{ill|lt=Sano Genzaemon|Q11385069|WD=Q11385069|1=Sano Genzaemon}} in the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205|1=Kamakura period}}, who revered {{ill|lt=Mishima Taisha|Q650772|WD=Q650772|lt=Mishima Shrine|1=Mishima Taisha}} in Izu, brought a cherry branch from there, and grafted it onto a tree in this shrine’s precinct. The shrine crest is a cherry emblem called “Sakurai-zakura.”

Originally it stood about 500 m north of the current site (Kayadō<ref name="kn2">''Commemorative Journal II: Exploring Changes in Architectural Culture in Kurobe City'' (February 20, 2008, Toyama Prefecture Architects Association Kurobe Branch), p.14.</ref>), but after shrine buildings, treasures, and old documents were lost to fire in the Nagao clan’s warfare during the {{ill|lt=Eiroku|Q1143341|WD=Q1143341|1=Eiroku}} era ({{ill|lt=1558|Q6601|WD=Q6601|1=1558}}-{{ill|lt=1570|Q6659|WD=Q6659|1=1570}})<ref name="rs" /><ref name="p330" />, it was moved to the present site in {{ill|lt=1580|Q6712|WD=Q6712|1=1580}} ({{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|WD=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 8). After major reconstruction of shrine buildings in {{ill|lt=1688|Q7671|WD=Q7671|1=1688}} ({{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 1)<ref name="kn2" />, it reverted to its pre-Kamakura shrine name “Yagokorōoichihiko Shrine” after the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}<ref name="p330" />, and in August {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 6) was ranked as the first prefectural shrine in the lower Shin-kawa region<ref>''Mishima Community Center New Building Commemoration: Then and Now of Mishima Town in Photos'' (September 1, 1995, Mishima Town Neighborhood Association), p.122.</ref>. On {{ill|lt=June 24|Q2665|WD=Q2665|1=June 24}}, {{ill|lt=1925|Q18107|WD=Q18107|1=1925}} ({{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|WD=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 14), Shinmei Shrine in Tenjinshin, {{ill|lt=Ishida Village (Toyama)|Q11587014|WD=Q11587014|lt=Ishida Village|1=Ishida}} (enshrining Amaterasu-Ōmikami), and household earth deities were {{ill|lt=shrine-merged|Q11590700|WD=Q11590700|lt=merged|1=Shrine Consolidation Policy}} (an earth mound was built under the large zelkova at this time)<ref name="p330" /><ref name="tt">''Toyama Encyclopedia, Vol. 2'' (August 1, 1994, Kita-Nippon Shimbun), p.978.</ref>. On {{ill|lt=October 25|Q2954|WD=Q2954|1=October 25}}, {{ill|lt=1942|Q18625|WD=Q18625|1=1942}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 17), the current shrine buildings using cypress from imperial Kiso timber were completed (transfer rites took place the day before, {{ill|lt=October 24|Q2955|WD=Q2955|1=October 24}})<ref name="p330" /><ref>''Mishima Community Center New Building Commemoration: Then and Now of Mishima Town in Photos'' (September 1, 1995, Mishima Town Neighborhood Association), p.124.</ref>. The precinct was expanded at the same time<ref name="kn2" />. Since then, grounds and facilities have been developed progressively<ref name="p330" />.

From {{ill|lt=2020|Q25337|WD=Q25337|1=2020}} ({{ill|lt=Reiwa|Q62609017|WD=Q62609017|1=Reiwa era}} 2), work was carried out to replace the copper roof plating, completed in November {{ill|lt=2021|Q49628|WD=Q49628|1=2021}} (Reiwa 3)<ref>''{{ill|lt=Kita-Nippon Shimbun|Q11401857|WD=Q11401857|1=The Kitanippon Shimbun}}'', Jan 17, 2022, p.6, “Our Town from the Sky: Mikkaichi, Kurobe City.”</ref>.

=== Facilities ===
[[File:Mishima-no-Ookeyaki019.jpg|thumb|Mishima’s great zelkova]]
The precinct has been designated a Kurobe City {{ill|lt=historic site|Q1081138|WD=Q1081138|1=Historic site}} since {{ill|lt=July 11|Q2701|WD=Q2701|1=July 11}}, {{ill|lt=1955|Q18577|WD=Q18577|1=1955}}. “Sakurai no Bakefuji” and “Mishima no Ōkeyaki” in detached precinct land (once part of the large original grounds but later separated) are city-designated natural monuments (designated {{ill|lt=February 1|Q2312|WD=Q2312|1=February 1}}, {{ill|lt=1965|Q2650|WD=Q2650|1=1965}} and {{ill|lt=September 28|Q2883|WD=Q2883|1=September 28}}, {{ill|lt=1983|Q2434|WD=Q2434|1=1983}}, respectively)<ref>[https://www.pref.toyama.jp/documents/14279/07-kurobe.pdf Cultural Properties of Kurobe City No.7] (Toyama Prefecture, accessed December 10, 2022)</ref>.

{{ill|lt=Chicken|Q780|WD=Q780|lt=Chickens|1=Chicken}} are treated as {{ill|lt=divine messengers|Q10444973|WD=Q10444973|1=Shinshi}}, and nearby people reportedly did not eat either meat or eggs<ref name="tt" />. There also remains an {{ill|lt=ema|Q687288|WD=Q687288|1=Ema (Shinto)}} of a chicken dedicated in {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1689|Q7674|WD=Q7674|1=1689}}).

